T1  - Effect of nicotinamide riboside on airway inflammation in COPD: a randomized, placebo-controlled trial.
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1038/s43587-024-00758-1
A1  - Norheim, Kristoffer L
A1  - Ben Ezra, Michael
A1  - Heckenbach, Indra
A1  - Andreasson, Louise Munkholm
A1  - Eriksen, Lise Lotte
A1  - Dyhre-Petersen, Nanna
A1  - Damgaard, Mads Vargas
A1  - Berglind, Magnus
A1  - Pricolo, Luca
A1  - Sampson, Dayle
A1  - Dellinger, Ryan W
A1  - Sverrild, Asger
A1  - Treebak, Jonas T
A1  - Ditlev, Sisse Bolm
A1  - Porsbjerg, Celeste
A1  - Scheibye-Knudsen, Morten
Y1  - 2024//
Y2  - 20241115//
N2  - Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) is a progressive, incurable disease associated with smoking and advanced age, ranking as the third leading cause of death worldwide. DNA damage and loss of the central metabolite nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+) may contribute to both aging and COPD, presenting a potential avenue for interventions. In this randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled clinical trial, we treated patients with stable COPD (n = 40) with the NAD+ precursor nicotinamide riboside (NR) for 6 weeks and followed-up 12 weeks later. The primary outcome was change in sputum interleukin-8 (IL-8) from baseline to week 6. The estimated treatment difference between NR and placebo in IL-8 after 6 weeks was -52.6% (95% confidence interval (CI): -75.7% to -7.6%; P = 0.030). This effect persisted until the follow-up 12 weeks after the end of treatment (-63.7%: 95% CI -85.7% to -7.8%; P = 0.034). For secondary outcomes, NR treatment increased NAD+ levels by more than twofold in whole blood, whereas IL-6 levels in plasma remained unchanged. In exploratory analyses, treatment with NR showed indications of upregulated gene pathways related to genomic integrity in the airways and reduced epigenetic aging, possibly through a reduction in cellular senescence. These exploratory analyses need to be confirmed in future trials. ClinicalTrials.gov identifier: NCT04990869 . Copyright © 2024. The Author(s).
